Common Newbie Mistakes and Bad Practices in Rust: Bad HabitsRust 中常见的新手错误和不良做法：不良习惯

September 27, 2021 22-minute read2021 年 9 月 27 日 22 分钟阅读
Rust • Best PracticesRust • 最佳实践

When you are coming to Rust from another language you bring all your previous experiences with you.当你从另一种语言转向 Rust 时，你会带来所有以前的经验。

Often this is awesome because it means you aren’t learning programming from scratch! However, you can also bring along bad habits which can lead you down the wrong rabbit hole or make you write bad code.这通常很棒，因为这意味着您不是从头开始学习编程！但是，您也可能会带上坏习惯，这些坏习惯可能会让您误入歧途或写出糟糕的代码。

The code written in this article is available on the Rust Playground using the various (playground) links dotted throughout. Feel free to browse through and steal code or inspiration.本文中编写的代码可在 Rust Playground 上使用贯穿始终的各种（游乐场）链接获得。随意浏览并窃取代码或灵感。

If you found this useful or spotted a bug in the article, let me know on the blog’s issue tracker!如果您发现本文有用或发现文章中的错误，请在博客的问题跟踪器上告诉我！

Using Sentinel Values Link to heading使用哨兵值

This one is a pet peeve of mine.这是我的宠儿。

In most C-based languages (C, C#, Java, etc.), the way you indicate whether something failed or couldn’t be found is by returning a “special” value. For example, C#’s String.IndexOf() method will scan an array for a particular element and return its index. Returning -1 if nothing is found.在大多数基于 C 的语言（C、C#、Java 等）中，指示某项是否失败或无法找到的方法是返回一个“特殊”值。例如，C# 的 String.IndexOf() 方法将扫描数组以查找特定元素并返回其索引。如果没有找到则返回 -1。

That leads to code like this:这导致了这样的代码：

string sentence = "The fox jumps over the dog";

int index = sentence.IndexOf("fox");

if (index != -1)
{
  string wordsAfterFox = sentence.SubString(index);
  Console.WriteLine(wordsAfterFox);
}

You see this sort of “use a sentinel value to indicate something special” practice all the time. Other sentinel values you might find in the wild are "", or null (someone once referred to this as their “billion-dollar mistake”).你经常看到这种“使用标记值来指示特殊事物”的做法。您可能在野外发现的其他标记值是 "" 或 null（有人曾将其称为“十亿美元的错误”）。

The general reason why this is a bad idea is that there is absolutely nothing to stop you from forgetting that check. That means you can accidentally crash your application with one misplaced assumption or when the code generating the sentinel is far away from the code using it.这是一个坏主意的一般原因是绝对没有什么可以阻止你忘记那张支票。这意味着您可能会因为一个错误的假设或生成哨兵的代码与使用它的代码相距甚远而意外地使您的应用程序崩溃。

We can do a lot better in Rust, though. Just use Option!不过，我们可以在 Rust 中做得更好。只需使用选项！

By design, there is no way to get the underlying value without dealing with the possibility that your Option may be None. This is enforced by the compiler at compile time, meaning code that forgets to check won’t even compile.按照设计，如果不处理您的 Option 可能为 None 的可能性，就无法获得潜在价值。这是由编译器在编译时强制执行的，这意味着忘记检查的代码甚至不会编译。

let sentence = "The fox jumps over the dog";
let index = sentence.find("fox");

// let words_after_fox = &sentence[index..]; // Error: Can't index str with Option<usize>

if let Some(fox) = index {
  let words_after_fox = &sentence[fox..];
  println!("{}", words_after_fox);
}

Hungarian Notation Link to heading匈牙利符号

Back in the 70’s, a naming convention called Hungarian Notation was developed by programmers writing in languages where variables are untyped or dynamically typed. It works by adding a mnemonic to the start of a name to indicate what it represents, for example the boolean visited variable might be called bVisited or the string name might be called strName.早在 70 年代，程序员就使用非类型化或动态类型化变量的语言编写了一种称为匈牙利表示法的命名约定。它通过在名称的开头添加助记符来指示它代表什么来工作，例如布尔访问变量可能称为 bVisited 或字符串名称可能称为 strName。

You can still see this naming convention in languages Delphi where classes (types) start with T, fields start with F, arguments start with A, and so on.您仍然可以在 Delphi 语言中看到这种命名约定，其中类（类型）以 T 开头，字段以 F 开头，参数以 A 开头，等等。

type
 TKeyValue = class
  private
    FKey: integer;
    FValue: TObject;
  public
    property Key: integer read FKey write FKey;
    property Value: TObject read FValue write FValue;
    function Frobnicate(ASomeArg: string): string;
  end;

C# also has a convention that all interfaces should start with I, meaning programmers coming to Rust from C# will sometimes prefix their traits with I as well.C# 也有一个约定，所有接口都应该以 I 开头，这意味着从 C# 转向 Rust 的程序员有时也会在他们的特征前加上 I。

trait IClone {
  fn clone(&self) -> Self;
}

In this case, just drop the leading I. Rust’s syntax guarantees that it just isn’t possible to confuse a trait for a normal type, so it isn’t helping anyone. This is in contrast with C# where interfaces and classes are largely interchangeable.在这种情况下，只需删除前导 I。Rust 的语法保证不可能将 trait 与普通类型混淆，因此它对任何人都没有帮助。这与接口和类在很大程度上可以互换的 C# 形成对比。

This is also seen inside functions where people will conjure up new names for something as they convert it from one form to another. Often these names are silly or contrived, providing negligible additional information to the reader.这也可以在函数内部看到，人们会在将某物从一种形式转换为另一种形式时为它想出新名称。这些名称通常很愚蠢或做作，为读者提供的附加信息微不足道。

let account_bytes: Vec<u8> = read_some_input();
let account_str = String::from_utf8(account_bytes)?;
let account: Account = account_str.parse()?;

I mean, if we’re calling String::from_utf8() we already know account_str will be a String so why add the _str suffix?我的意思是，如果我们调用 String::from_utf8() 我们已经知道 account_str 将是一个字符串那么为什么要添加 _str 后缀？

Unlike a lot of other languages, Rust encourages shadowing variables when you are transforming them from one form to another, especially when the previous variable is no longer accessible (e.g. because it’s been moved).与许多其他语言不同，当您将变量从一种形式转换为另一种形式时，Rust 鼓励隐藏变量，尤其是当先前的变量不再可访问时（例如，因为它已被移动）。

let account: Vec<u8> = read_some_input();
let account = String::from_utf8(account)?;
let account: Account = account.parse()?;

This is arguably superior because we can use the same name for the same concept.这可以说是优越的，因为我们可以对相同的概念使用相同的名称。

Other languages frown on shadowing because it can be easy to lose track of what type a variable contains (e.g. in a dynamically typed language like JavaScript) or you can introduce bugs where the programmer thinks a variable has one type but it actually contains something separate.其他语言不赞成阴影，因为它很容易忘记变量包含的类型（例如，在像 JavaScript 这样的动态类型语言中），或者您可能会引入错误，程序员认为变量具有一种类型但实际上包含不同的东西。

Neither of these is particularly relevant to a strongly typed language with move semantics like Rust, so you can use shadowing freely without worrying about shooting yourself in the foot.这些都与像 Rust 这样具有移动语义的强类型语言特别相关，因此您可以自由地使用阴影而不用担心搬起石头砸自己的脚。

An Abundance of Rc<RefCell<T>> Link to heading丰富的 Rc<RefCell<T>>

A common pattern in Object Oriented languages is to accept a reference to some object so you can call its methods later on.面向对象语言中的一个常见模式是接受对某个对象的引用，以便稍后调用它的方法。

On its own there is nothing wrong with this, Dependency Injection is a very good thing to do, but unlike most OO languages Rust doesn’t have a garbage collector and has strong feelings on shared mutability.这本身并没有错，依赖注入是一件非常好的事情，但与大多数 OO 语言不同，Rust 没有垃圾收集器并且对共享可变性有强烈的感觉。

Perhaps this will be easier to understand with an example.也许用一个例子会更容易理解。

Say we are implementing a game where the player needs to beat up a bunch of monsters until they have inflicted a certain amount of damage (I dunno, maybe it’s for a quest or something).假设我们正在实现一个游戏，玩家需要打败一堆怪物，直到它们造成一定程度的伤害（我不知道，也许是为了任务或其他什么）。

We create a Monster class which has a health property and a takeDamage() method, and so we can keep track of how much damage has been inflicted we’ll let people provide callbacks that get called whenever the monster receives damage.我们创建了一个 Monster 类，它有一个 health 属性和一个 takeDamage() 方法，这样我们就可以跟踪造成了多少伤害，我们将让人们提供每当怪物受到伤害时调用的回调。

type OnReceivedDamage = (damageReceived: number) => void;

class Monster {
    health: number = 50;
    receivedDamage: OnReceivedDamage[] = [];

    takeDamage(amount: number) {
        amount = Math.min(this.health, amount);
        this.health -= amount;
        this.receivedDamage.forEach(cb => cb(amount));
    }

    on(event: "damaged", callback: OnReceivedDamage): void {
        this.receivedDamage.push(callback);
    }
}

Let’s also create a DamageCounter class which tracks how much damage we’ve inflicted and lets us know when that goal is reached.我们还创建一个 DamageCounter 类来跟踪我们造成了多少伤害，并在达到目标时通知我们。

class DamageCounter {
    damageInflicted: number = 0;

    reachedTargetDamage(): boolean {
        return this.damageInflicted > 100;
    }

    onDamageInflicted(amount: number) {
        this.damageInflicted += amount;
    }
}

Now we’ll create some monsters and keep inflicting a random amount of damage until the DamageCounter is happy.现在我们将创建一些怪物并持续造成随机数量的伤害，直到 DamageCounter 满意为止。

const counter = new DamageCounter();

const monsters = [new Monster(), new Monster(), new Monster(), new Monster(), new Monster()];
monsters.forEach(m => m.on("damaged", amount => counter.onDamageInflicted(amount)));

while (!counter.reachedTargetDamage()) {
    // pick a random monster
    const index = Math.floor(Math.random()*monsters.length);
    const target = monsters[index];
    // then damage it a bit
    const damage = Math.round(Math.random() * 50);
    target.takeDamage(damage);

    console.log(`Monster ${index} received ${damage} damage`);
}

(TypeScript Playground)（打字稿游乐场）

Now let’s port this code to Rust. Our Monster struct is fairly similar, although we need to use Box<dyn Fn(u32)> for a closure which accepts a single u32 argument (all closures in JavaScript are heap allocated by default).现在让我们将这段代码移植到 Rust。我们的 Monster 结构非常相似，尽管我们需要将 Box<dyn Fn(u32)> 用于接受单个 u32 参数的闭包（默认情况下，JavaScript 中的所有闭包都是堆分配的）。

type OnReceivedDamage = Box<dyn Fn(u32)>;

struct Monster {
    health: u32,
    received_damage: Vec<OnReceivedDamage>,
}

impl Monster {
    fn take_damage(&mut self, amount: u32) {
        let damage_received = cmp::min(self.health, amount);
        self.health -= damage_received;
        for callback in &mut self.received_damage {
            callback(damage_received);
        }
    }

    fn add_listener(&mut self, listener: OnReceivedDamage) {
        self.received_damage.push(listener);
    }
}

impl Default for Monster {
    fn default() -> Self {
        Monster { health: 100, received_damage: Vec::new() }
    }
}

Next comes our DamageCounter, nothing interesting here.接下来是我们的 DamageCounter，这里没什么有趣的。

#[derive(Default)]
struct DamageCounter {
    damage_inflicted: u32,
}

impl DamageCounter {
    fn reached_target_damage(&self) -> bool {
        self.damage_inflicted > 100
    }

    fn on_damage_received(&mut self, damage: u32) {
        self.damage_inflicted += damage;
    }
}

And finally our code that inflicts damage.最后是我们造成损害的代码。

fn main() {
    let mut rng = rand::thread_rng();
    let mut counter = DamageCounter::default();
    let mut monsters: Vec<_> = (0..5).map(|_| Monster::default()).collect();

    for monster in &mut monsters {
        monster.add_listener(Box::new(|damage| counter.on_damage_received(damage)));
    }

    while !counter.reached_target_damage() {
        let index = rng.gen_range(0..monsters.len());
        let target = &mut monsters[index];

        let damage = rng.gen_range(0..50);
        target.take_damage(damage);

        println!("Monster {} received {} damage", index, damage);
    }
}

But herein lies our first problem, when we try to compile the code rustc gives us not one, but four compile errors for the monster.add_listener() line 🤣但这就是我们的第一个问题，当我们尝试编译代码时，rustc 给我们提供的不是一个，而是四个 monster.add_listener() 行的编译错误🤣

There are a number of things wrong with this line, but it can be boiled down to:这条线有很多问题，但可以归结为：

  • The closure captures a reference to counter闭包捕获对计数器的引用
  • The counter.on_damage_received() method takes &mut self so our closure needs a &mut reference. We add the closures in a loop so we end up taking multiple &mut references to the same object at the same timecounter.on_damage_received() 方法接受 &mut self 所以我们的闭包需要一个 &mut 引用。我们在循环中添加闭包，所以我们最终同时对同一个对象进行多个 &mut 引用
  • Our listener is a boxed closure without any lifetime annotations, meaning it needs to own any variables it closes over. We would need to move the counter into the closure, but because we do this in a loop we’ll have a “use of moved value” error我们的侦听器是一个没有任何生命周期注释的盒装闭包，这意味着它需要拥有它关闭的任何变量。我们需要将计数器移动到闭包中，但是因为我们在循环中执行此操作，所以会出现“使用移动值”错误
  • After passing the counter to add_listener() we try to use it in our loop condition将计数器传递给 add_listener() 后，我们尝试在循环条件中使用它

Overall it’s just a bad situation.总的来说，这只是一个糟糕的情况。

The canonical answer to this is to wrap the DamageCounter in a reference-counted pointer so we can have multiple handles to it at the same time, then because we need to call a &mut self method we also need a RefCell to “move” the borrow checking from compile time to run time.对此的规范答案是将 DamageCounter 包装在一个引用计数的指针中，这样我们就可以同时拥有多个句柄，然后因为我们需要调用 &mut self 方法，我们还需要一个 RefCell 来“移动”借用从编译时检查到运行时。

 fn main() {
     let mut rng = rand::thread_rng();
-    let mut counter = DamageCounter::default();
+    let mut counter = Rc::new(RefCell::new(DamageCounter::default()));
     let mut monsters: Vec<_> = (0..5).map(|_| Monster::default()).collect();

     for monster in &mut monsters {
-        monster.add_listener(Box::new(|damage| counter.on_damage_received(damage)));
+        let counter = Rc::clone(&counter);
+        monster.add_listener(Box::new(move |damage| {
+            counter.borrow_mut().on_damage_received(damage)
+        }));
     }

-    while !counter.reached_target_damage() {
+    while !counter.borrow().reached_target_damage() {
         let index = rng.gen_range(0..monsters.len());
         let target = &mut monsters[index];
         ...
     }
 }

(playground)（操场）

Well… it works. But this approach tends to get messy, especially when you are storing non-trivial things like a Rc<RefCell<Vec<Foo>>>> (or its multi-threaded cousin Arc<Mutex<Vec<Foo>>>>) inside structs 1.好吧……它有效。但是这种方法往往会变得混乱，尤其是当您在内部存储诸如 Rc<RefCell<Vec<Foo>>>>（或其多线程表亲 Arc<Mutex<Vec<Foo>>>>）之类的重要内容时结构 1.

It also opens you up to situations where the RefCell might be borrowed mutably multiple times because your code is complex and something higher up in the call stack is already using the RefCell. With a Mutex this will cause a deadlock while the RefCell will panic, neither of which is conducive to a reliable program.它还会让您面临 RefCell 可能被多次可变借用的情况，因为您的代码很复杂，并且调用堆栈中更高层的东西已经在使用 RefCell。对于 Mutex，这将导致死锁，而 RefCell 将崩溃，这两种情况都不利于可靠的程序。

A much better approach is to change your API to not hold long-lived references to other objects. Depending on the situation, it might make sense to take a callback argument in the Monster::take_damage() method.一个更好的方法是更改​​您的 API 以不保存对其他对象的长期引用。根据情况，在 Monster::take_damage() 方法中使用回调参数可能是有意义的。

struct Monster {
    health: u32,
}

impl Monster {
    fn take_damage(&mut self, amount: u32, on_damage_received: impl FnOnce(u32)) {
        let damage_received = cmp::min(self.health, amount);
        self.health -= damage_received;
        on_damage_received(damage_received);
    }
}

impl Default for Monster {
  fn default() -> Self { Monster { health: 100 } }
}

...

fn main() {
    let mut rng = rand::thread_rng();
    let mut counter = DamageCounter::default();
    let mut monsters: Vec<_> = (0..5).map(|_| Monster::default()).collect();

    while !counter.reached_target_damage() {
        let index = rng.gen_range(0..monsters.len());
        let target = &mut monsters[index];

        let damage = rng.gen_range(0..50);
        target.take_damage(damage, |dmg| counter.on_damage_received(dmg));

        println!("Monster {} received {} damage", index, damage);
    }
}

(playground)（操场）

A nice side-effect of this is that we get rid of all the callback management boilerplate, meaning this version is only 47 lines long instead of the Rc<RefCell<_>> version’s 62.一个很好的副作用是我们摆脱了所有回调管理样板，这意味着这个版本只有 47 行长而不是 Rc<RefCell<_>> 版本的 62 行。

Other times it may not be acceptable to give take_damage() a callback parameter, in which case you could return a “summary” of what happened so the caller can decide what to do next.其他时候，给 take_damage() 一个回调参数可能是不可接受的，在这种情况下，您可以返回发生的事情的“摘要”，以便调用者可以决定下一步做什么。

impl Monster {
    fn take_damage(&mut self, amount: u32) -> AttackSummary {
        let damage_received = cmp::min(self.health, amount);
        self.health -= damage_received;
        AttackSummary { damage_received }
    }
}

struct AttackSummary {
    damage_received: u32,
}

...

fn main() {
    let mut rng = rand::thread_rng();
    let mut counter = DamageCounter::default();
    let mut monsters: Vec<_> = (0..5).map(|_| Monster::default()).collect();

    while !counter.reached_target_damage() {
        let index = rng.gen_range(0..monsters.len());
        let target = &mut monsters[index];

        let damage = rng.gen_range(0..50);
        let AttackSummary { damage_received } = target.take_damage(damage);
        counter.on_damage_received(damage_received);

        println!("Monster {} received {} damage", index, damage);
    }
}

(playground)（操场）

This is my preferred solution; from experience, it tends to work well for larger codebases or when the code is more complex.这是我的首选解决方案；根据经验，它往往适用于较大的代码库或代码更复杂的情况。

Using the Wrong Integer Type Link to heading使用错误的整数类型

Another hang-over from writing a lot of C is using the wrong integer type and getting frustrated because you need to cast to/from usize all the time.编写大量 C 语言的另一个后遗症是使用了错误的整数类型，并且因为您需要一直转换到 usize 或从 usize 转换而感到沮丧。

I’ve seen people run into this so many times in the wild, especially when indexing.我已经看到人们在野外多次遇到这种情况，尤其是在索引时。

The underlying problem is that C programmers are all taught to use int for indexing and for-loops, so when they come to Rust and they need to store a list of indices, the programmer will immediately reach for a Vec<i32>. They then get frustrated because Rust is quite strict when it comes to indexing and standard types like arrays, slices, and Vec can only be indexed using usize (the equivalent of size_t), meaning their code is cluttered with casts from i32 to usize and back again.潜在的问题是 C 程序员都被教导使用 int 进行索引和 for 循环，所以当他们使用 Rust 并且需要存储索引列表时，程序员将立即找到 Vec<i32>。然后他们会感到沮丧，因为 Rust 在索引和标准类型（如数组、切片和 Vec 等）方面非常严格，只能使用 usize（相当于 size_t）进行索引，这意味着他们的代码充满了从 i32 到 usize 和返回的强制转换再次。

There are a number of perfectly legitimate reasons for why Rust only allows indexing by usize:有许多完全合理的理由可以解释为什么 Rust 只允许通过 usize 进行索引：

  • It doesn’t make sense to have a negative index (accessing items before the start of a slice is UB), so we can avoid an entire class of bugs by indexing with an unsigned integer负索引没有意义（访问切片开始之前的项目是 UB），因此我们可以通过使用无符号整数进行索引来避免一整类错误
  • A usize is defined to be an integer with the same size as a normal pointer, meaning the pointer arithmetic won’t have any hidden castsusize 被定义为一个与普通指针大小相同的整数，这意味着指针算法不会有任何隐藏的转换
  • The std::mem::size_of() and std::mem::align_of() functions return usizestd::mem::size_of() 和 std::mem::align_of() 函数返回 usize

Of course, when stated this way the solution is clear. Choose the right integer type for your application but when you are doing things that eventually be used for indexing, that “right integer type” is probably usize.当然，当这样说时，解决方案就很清楚了。为您的应用程序选择正确的整数类型，但是当您执行最终用于索引的操作时，可能会使用“正确的整数类型”。

Unsafe - I Know What I’m Doing Link to heading不安全——我知道我在做什么

<rant><咆哮>

There’s an old Rust koan on the User Forums by Daniel Keep that comes to mind every time I see a grizzled C programmer reach for raw pointers or std::mem::transmute() because the borrow checker keeps rejecting their code: Obstacles.每当我看到一个头发花白的 C 程序员使用原始指针或 std::mem::transmute() 因为借用检查器一直拒绝他们的代码时，Daniel Keep 在用户论坛上有一个古老的 Rust 公案会浮现在脑海中：障碍。

You should go read it. It’s okay, I’ll wait.你应该去读它。没关系，我会等。

Too often you see people wanting to hack around privacy, create self-referencing structs, or create global mutable variables using unsafe. Frequently this will be accompanied by comments like “but I know this program will only use a single thread so accessing the static mut is fine” or “but this works perfectly fine in C”.您经常会看到人们想要绕过隐私、创建自引用结构或使用 unsafe 创建全局可变变量。这通常会伴随着评论，例如“但我知道这个程序将只使用一个线程，所以访问静态 mut 没问题”或“但这在 C 中工作得很好”。

The reality is that unsafe code is nuanced and you need to have a good intuition for Rust’s borrow checking rules and memory model. I hate to be a gate keeper and say “you must be this tall to write multi-threaded unsafe code” 2, but there’s a good chance that if you are new to the language you won’t have this intuition and are opening yourself and your colleagues up to a lot of pain.事实上，不安全代码是微妙的，你需要对 Rust 的借用检查规则和内存模型有很好的直觉。我讨厌成为守门人并说“你必须这么高才能编写多线程不安全代码”2，但是如果你是这门语言的新手，很有可能你不会有这种直觉并且正在打开自己和你的同事最多痛苦很多。

It’s fine to play around with unsafe if you are trying to learn more about Rust or you know what you are doing and are using it legitimately, but unsafe is not a magical escape hatch which will make the compiler stop complaining and let you write C with Rust syntax.如果你想了解更多关于 Rust 的知识，或者你知道自己在做什么并且正在合法地使用它，那么使用 unsafe 是很好的，但是 unsafe 并不是一个神奇的逃生口，它会让编译器停止抱怨并让你用锈语法。

</rant></咆哮>

Not Using Namespaces Link to heading不使用命名空间

A common practice in C is to prefix functions with the name of the library or module to help readers understand where it comes from and avoid duplicate symbol errors (e.g. rune_wasmer_runtime_load()).C 中的一个常见做法是在函数前加上库或模块的名称，以帮助读者了解它的来源并避免重复符号错误（例如 rune_wasmer_runtime_load()）。

However, Rust has real namespaces and lets you attach methods to types (e.g. rune::wasmer::Runtime::load()). Just use them - it’s what they are there for.但是，Rust 具有真正的名称空间，并允许您将方法附加到类型（例如 rune::wasmer::Runtime::load()）。只需使用它们 - 这就是它们的用途。

Overusing Slice Indexing Link to heading过度使用切片索引

The for-loop and indexing is the bread and butter for most C-based languages.for 循环和索引是大多数基于 C 的语言的基础。

let points: Vec<Coordinate> = ...;
let differences = Vec::new();

for i in 1..points.len() [
  let current = points[i];
  let previous = points[i-1];
  differences.push(current - previous);
]

(playground)（操场）

However, it’s easy to accidentally introduce an off-by-one error when using indexing (e.g. I needed to remember to start looping from 1 and subtract 1 to get the previous point) and even seasoned programmers aren’t immune from crashing due to an index-out-of-bounds error.但是，在使用索引时很容易意外引入差一错误（例如，我需要记住从 1 开始循环并减去 1 以获得前一个点），即使是经验丰富的程序员也无法避免由于索引越界错误。

In situations like these, Rust encourages you to reach for iterators instead. The slice type even comes with high-level tools like the windows() and array_windows() methods to let you iterate over adjacent pairs of elements.在这种情况下，Rust 鼓励您改用迭代器。 slice 类型甚至带有高级工具，例如 windows() 和 array_windows() 方法，可让您迭代相邻的元素对。

let points: Vec<Coordinate> = ...;
let mut differences = Vec::new();

for [previous, current] in points.array_windows().copied() {
  differences.push(current - previous);
}

(playground)（操场）

You could even remove the for-loop and mutation of differences altogether.您甚至可以完全删除 for 循环和差异突变。

let differences: Vec<_> = points
  .array_windows()
  .copied()
  .map(|[previous, current]| current - previous)
  .collect();

(playground)（操场）

Some would argue the version with map() and collect() is cleaner or more “functional”, but I’ll let you be the judge there.有些人会争辩说带有 map() 和 collect() 的版本更简洁或更“实用”，但我会让你来判断。

As a bonus, iterators can often allow better performance because checks can be done as part of the looping condition instead of being separate3 (Alice has a good explanation here).作为奖励，迭代器通常可以提供更好的性能，因为检查可以作为循环条件的一部分而不是单独进行3（爱丽丝在这里有一个很好的解释）。

Overusing Iterators Link to heading过度使用迭代器

Once you start drinking the Kool-Aid that is Rust’s iterators you can run into the opposite problem - when all you have is a hammer everything looks like a nail.一旦你开始喝 Rust 的迭代器 Kool-Aid，你就会遇到相反的问题——当你只有一把锤子时，一切看起来都像钉子。

Long chains of map(), filter(), and and_then() calls can get quite hard to read and keep track of what is actually going on, especially when type inference lets you omit a closure argument’s type.长链的 map()、filter() 和 and_then() 调用会变得很难阅读和跟踪实际发生的事情，尤其是当类型推断允许您忽略闭包参数的类型时。

Other times your iterator-based solution is just unnecessarily complicated.其他时候，基于迭代器的解决方案只是不必要地复杂。

As an example, have a look at this snippet of code and see if you can figure out what it is trying to do.例如，看看这段代码，看看您是否能弄清楚它试图做什么。

pub fn functional_blur(input: &Matrix) -> Matrix {
    assert!(input.width >= 3);
    assert!(input.height >= 3);

    // Stash away the top and bottom rows so they can be
    // directly copied across later
    let mut rows = input.rows();
    let first_row = rows.next().unwrap();
    let last_row = rows.next_back().unwrap();

    let top_row = input.rows();
    let middle_row = input.rows().skip(1);
    let bottom_row = input.rows().skip(2);

    let blurred_elements = top_row
        .zip(middle_row)
        .zip(bottom_row)
        .flat_map(|((top, middle), bottom)| blur_rows(top, middle, bottom));

    let elements: Vec<f32> = first_row
        .iter()
        .copied()
        .chain(blurred_elements)
        .chain(last_row.iter().copied())
        .collect();

    Matrix::new_row_major(elements, input.width, input.height)
}

fn blur_rows<'a>(
    top_row: &'a [f32],
    middle_row: &'a [f32],
    bottom_row: &'a [f32],
) -> impl Iterator<Item = f32> + 'a {
    // stash away the left-most and right-most elements so they can be copied across directly.
    let &first = middle_row.first().unwrap();
    let &last = middle_row.last().unwrap();

    // Get the top, middle, and bottom row of our 3x3 sub-matrix so they can be
    // averaged.
    let top_window = top_row.windows(3);
    let middle_window = middle_row.windows(3);
    let bottom_window = bottom_row.windows(3);

    // slide the 3x3 window across our middle row so we can get the average
    // of everything except the left-most and right-most elements.
    let averages = top_window
        .zip(middle_window)
        .zip(bottom_window)
        .map(|((top, middle), bottom)| top.iter().chain(middle).chain(bottom).sum::<f32>() / 9.0);

    std::iter::once(first)
        .chain(averages)
        .chain(std::iter::once(last))
}

(playground)（操场）

Believe it or not, but that’s one of the more readable versions I’ve seen… Now let’s look at the imperative implementation.信不信由你，但这是我见过的更具可读性的版本之一……现在让我们看看命令式实现。

pub fn imperative_blur(input: &Matrix) -> Matrix {
    assert!(input.width >= 3);
    assert!(input.height >= 3);

    // allocate our output matrix, copying from the input so
    // we don't need to worry about the edge cases.
    let mut output = input.clone();

    for y in 1..(input.height - 1) {
        for x in 1..(input.width - 1) {
            let mut pixel_value = 0.0;

            pixel_value += input[[x - 1, y - 1]];
            pixel_value += input[[x, y - 1]];
            pixel_value += input[[x + 1, y - 1]];

            pixel_value += input[[x - 1, y]];
            pixel_value += input[[x, y]];
            pixel_value += input[[x + 1, y]];

            pixel_value += input[[x - 1, y + 1]];
            pixel_value += input[[x, y + 1]];
            pixel_value += input[[x + 1, y + 1]];

            output[[x, y]] = pixel_value / 9.0;
        }
    }

    output
}

(playground)（操场）

I know which version I prefer.我知道我更喜欢哪个版本。

Not Leveraging Pattern Matching Link to heading不利用模式匹配

In most other mainstream languages it is quite common to see the programmer write a check before they do an operation which may throw an exception. Our C# IndexOf() snippet from earlier is a good example of this:在大多数其他主流语言中，经常会看到程序员在执行可能引发异常的操作之前写检查。我们之前的 C# IndexOf() 片段就是一个很好的例子：

int index = sentence.IndexOf("fox");

if (index != -1)
{
  string wordsAfterFox = sentence.SubString(index);
  Console.WriteLine(wordsAfterFox);
}

Closer to home, you might see code like this:言归正传，你可能会看到这样的代码：

let opt: Option<_> = ...;

if opt.is_some() {
  let value = opt.unwrap();
  ...
}

or this:或这个：

let list: &[f32] = ...;

if !list.is_empty() {
  let first = list[0];
  ...
}

Now both snippets are perfectly valid pieces of code and will never fail, but similar to sentinel values you are making it easy for future refactoring to introduce a bug.现在这两个片段都是完全有效的代码片段，永远不会失败，但与标记值类似，您可以让未来的重构更容易引入错误。

Using things like pattern matching and Option help you avoid this situation by making sure the only way you can access a value is if it is valid.使用模式匹配和选项之类的东西可以帮助您避免这种情况，因为您可以确保访问值的唯一方式是它是否有效。

if let Some(value) = opt {
  ...
}

if let [first, ..] = list {
  ...
}

I’m sure most of you have seen if let Some(...) before, but if if let [first, ..] is unfamiliar you may find my article on Slice Patterns interesting.我相信你们中的大多数人以前都看过 if let Some(...)，但是如果 if let [first, ..] 不熟悉，您可能会发现我关于切片模式的文章很有趣。

Depending on where it is used and how smart LLVM or your CPU’s branch predictor are, this may also generate slower code because the fallible operation (opt.unwrap() or list[index] in that example) needs to do unnecessary checks 3.根据它的使用位置以及 LLVM 或 CPU 的分支预测器的智能程度，这也可能会生成较慢的代码，因为容易出错的操作（该示例中的 opt.unwrap() 或 list[index]）需要进行不必要的检查 3。

Initialize After Construction Link to heading构造后初始化

In many languages, it is normal to call an object’s constructor and initialize its fields afterward (either manually or by calling some init() method). However, this goes against Rust’s general convention of “make invalid states unrepresentable”.在许多语言中，通常调用对象的构造函数并随后初始化其字段（手动或通过调用某些 init() 方法）。然而，这违背了 Rust 的“使无效状态不可表示”的一般惯例。

Say you are writing an NLP application and have a dictionary containing all the possible words you can handle.假设您正在编写一个 NLP 应用程序，并且有一个包含您可以处理的所有可能单词的字典。

This is one way you could create the dictionary:这是创建字典的一种方式：

let mut dict = Dictionary::new();
// read the file and populate some internal HashMap or Vec
dict.load_from_file("./words.txt")?;

However, writing Dictionary this way means it now has two (hidden) states - empty and populated.然而，以这种方式编写 Dictionary 意味着它现在有两个（隐藏的）状态——空的和填充的。

All downstream code that uses the Dictionary will assume it’s been populated already and write code accordingly. This may include doing things like indexing into the dictionary with dict["word"] which may panic if "word" isn’t there.所有使用 Dictionary 的下游代码都将假定它已经被填充并相应地编写代码。这可能包括做一些事情，比如用 dict["word"] 索引到字典中，如果 "word" 不存在，它可能会恐慌。

Now you’ve opened yourself up to a situation where passing an empty dictionary to code that expects a populated dictionary may trigger a panic.现在您已经面临这样一种情况：将空字典传递给需要填充字典的代码可能会引发恐慌。

But that’s completely unnecessary.但这是完全没有必要的。

Just make sure the Dictionary is usable immediately after constructing it instead of populating it after the fact.只需确保 Dictionary 在构建后立即可用，而不是事后填充它。

let dict = Dictionary::from_file("./words.txt")?;

impl Dictionary {
  fn from_file(filename: impl AsRef<Path>) -> Result<Self, Error> {
    let text = std::fs::read_to_string(filename)?;
    let mut words = Vec::new();
    for line in text.lines() {
      words.push(line);
    }
    Ok(Dictionary { words })
  }
}

Internally the Dictionary::from_file() might create an empty Vec and populate it incrementally, but it won’t be stored in the Dictionary’s words field yet so there is no assumption that it is populated and useful.在内部 Dictionary::from_file() 可能会创建一个空的 Vec 并逐渐填充它，但它不会存储在 Dictionary 的单词字段中，因此没有假设它已填充和有用。

How frequently you fall into this anti-pattern depends a lot on your background and coding style.您陷入这种反模式的频率在很大程度上取决于您的背景和编码风格。

Functional languages are often completely immutable so you’ll fall into the idiomatic pattern naturally. After all, it’s kinda hard to create a half-initialized thing and populate it later when you aren’t allowed to mutate anything.函数式语言通常是完全不可变的，因此您会自然而然地陷入惯用模式。毕竟，创建一个半初始化的东西并在不允许更改任何东西时稍后填充它有点困难。

On the other hand, OO languages are much happier to let you initialize an object after it has been constructed, especially because object references can be null by default and they have no qualms about mutability… You could argue this contributes to why OO languages have a propensity for crashing due to an unexpected NullPointerException.另一方面，OO 语言更乐于让您在构造对象后对其进行初始化，尤其是因为默认情况下对象引用可以为 null，并且它们对可变性没有疑虑……您可能会争辩说这有助于解释为什么 OO 语言具有由于意外的 NullPointerException 而导致崩溃的倾向。

Defensive Copies Link to heading防御副本

To point out the obvious, a really nice property of immutable objects is that you can rely on them to never change. However, in languages like Python and Java, immutability isn’t transitive - i.e. if x is an immutable object, x.y isn’t guaranteed to be immutable unless it was explicitly defined that way.显而易见的是，不可变对象的一个​​非常好的属性是您可以依赖它们永远不会改变。但是，在 Python 和 Java 等语言中，不可变性不是可传递的——即如果 x 是一个不可变对象，则不能保证 x.y 是不可变的，除非以这种方式明确定义。

This means it’s possible to write code like this…这意味着可以编写这样的代码......

class ImmutablePerson:
  def __init__(self, name: str, age: int, addresses: List[str]):
    self._name = name
    self._age = age
    self._addresses = addresses

  # read-only properties
  @property
  def name(self): return self._name
  @property
  def age(self): return self._age
  @property
  def addresses(self): return self._addresses

Then someone else comes along and accidentally messes up the address list as part of their normal code.然后其他人出现并不小心弄乱了地址列表作为他们正常代码的一部分。

def send_letters(message: str, addresses: List[str]):
  # Note: the post office's API only works with with uppercase letters so we
  # need to pre-process the address list
  for i, address in enumerate(addresses):
    addresses[i] = addresses.upper()

  client = PostOfficeClient()
  client.send_bulk_mail(message, addresses)


person = ImmutablePerson("Joe Bloggs", 42, ["123 Fake Street"])

send_letters(
  f"Dear {person.name}, I Nigerian prince. Please help me moving my monies.",
  person.addresses
)

print(person.addresses) # ["123 FAKE STREET"]

While I admit the example is a bit contrived, it’s not uncommon for functions to modify the arguments they are given. Normally this is fine, but when your ImmutablePerson assumes its addresses field will never change, it’s annoying for some random piece of code on the other side of the project to modify it without you knowing.虽然我承认这个例子有点做作，但函数修改给定参数的情况并不少见。通常这很好，但是当你的 ImmutablePerson 假设它的地址字段永远不会改变时，项目另一端的一些随机代码在你不知情的情况下修改它是很烦人的。

The typical solution to this is to preemptively copy the list so even if the caller tries to mutate its contents, they’ll be mutating a copy and not the original addresses field.典型的解决方案是抢先复制列表，这样即使调用者试图改变其内容，他们也会改变副本而不是原始地址字段。

class ImmutablePerson:
  ...

  @property
  def addresses(self): return self._addresses.copy()

In general, you’ll see defensive copies being used anywhere code wants to be sure that another piece of code won’t modify some shared object at an inopportune time.通常，您会看到在任何代码想要确保另一段代码不会在不合时宜的时间修改某些共享对象的地方使用防御性副本。

Considering this is an article about Rust, you’ve probably guessed what the root cause of this is - a combination of aliasing and mutation.考虑到这是一篇关于 Rust 的文章，您可能已经猜到其根本原因是什么——别名和突变的结合。

You’ve also probably guessed why defensive copies aren’t really necessary when writing Rust code - lifetimes and the “shared immutable XOR single mutable” rule for references means it just isn’t possible for code to modify something without first asking its original owner for mutable access or explicitly opting into shared mutation by using a type like std::sync::Mutex<T>.你也可能猜到了为什么在编写 Rust 代码时防御副本并不是真正必要的——生命周期和引用的“共享不可变 XOR 单一可变”规则意味着代码不可能在不首先询问其原始所有者的情况下修改某些东西用于可变访问或通过使用类似 std::sync::Mutex<T> 的类型显式选择共享突变。

You may sometimes see people using clone() to get around borrow checker errors, and exclaim “Ha! See, Rust forces you to make defensive copies too!”有时您可能会看到人们使用 clone() 来绕过借用检查器错误，然后惊呼“哈！看，Rust 也迫使你制作防御性副本！”

To which I would argue that these copies are mostly caused by a lack of familiarity with lifetimes, or an architecture issue which forces the programmer to make more copies than they need to.对此我认为，这些副本主要是由于对生命周期不熟悉，或者是架构问题迫使程序员制作比他们需要的更多的副本。
